76561198011582886,Recommended,223830,10688447,"Posted: 22 June, 2014",all,tragicjoker34,"So far, this is a very faithful revision of the original X-COM.  The difficulty is very rewarding, and the game is quite engrossing."
,Recommended,223830,20945637,"Posted: 3 February, 2016",all,Trar [99th Calzones],"Full disclosure: I'm writing this review from the POV of someone who's certainly heard of but never played any of the Xcom games before starting this one.Xenonauts is a strategy game where you command the titular international military group tasked with defending Earth from alien invasion in the late 1970s. It's supposed to be a remake of the original X-Com set during the Cold War, and as far as I know it's a pretty faithful recreation right down to the battlefield, base placement and troop equipment micromanagement. It seems deeper than, say, the newer XCOM series, not that that would make the newer games bad.For me personally, it feels more like a classic Doctor Who serial without the Doctor or indeed almost any sense of optimism. (It doesn't really take advantage the fact that it's set during the Cold War - often you'll have NATO and Warsaw Pact soldiers working together in the same squad.) This game can be pretty brutal at times. The only thing that will save you from the nasty, aggressive aliens is attacking them wherever it's advantageous to do so with maximum firepower, then stealing their stuff so your scientists can reverse-engineer it into evenmorefirepower.I quite like it myself, and it's an impressive indie effort, so I'd say it's good...but given its problems it's just a little bit shy of 'great'. Let's hopethe sequelwill be great.My other observations:Air combat is ""aces"", perhaps the best expansion over the original X-Com, though it's 3v3 max and takes some getting used to. Make sure you don't insta-deploy to the first sight of UFO activity before formulating some sort of tactic for the situation, and make sure you know your aircrafts' limits before sending them out to fight.Breaching downed alien ships can become tedious - the devs should have added back doors, side entrances and/or destructible hull points to at least some of them. You pretty much need explosives, shields and/or expendable soldiers because at least some of the aliens will have holed up inside and theywillshoot the hell out of your troops.To my understanding, the original X-Com eventually gave you tools to counter psionic attacks and develop your own. Xenonauts doesn't seem to give you anything of the sort except letting your braver troops/those who survived previous psychic attacks resist them more effectively.Bullet trajectories aren't really modeled past your units' line of sight, from what I can tell. If you fire on where you know an alien is, but the alien is out of your LOS, it won't do anything unless you use projectile weapons such as rockets.Lines of sight themselves can be weird. Soldiers seem to have a difficult time throwing grenades over objects, but alien forces seem to be able to see your forces often before you can see them.Workshop support is truly this game's saving grace. There's already a number of mods that try to fix what I've described above.I would say this is a rather rough but ultimately enjoyable game for people who want a no-holds-barred slugfest with MiGs and M16s against invading aliens. It's certainly smoother around the edges for people who don't want to play the original, which is more than 20 years old at this point. It also seems more grim in tone than the original, but that could be just me.The prequel novella included with the game is good, at least.Two tips. Alien activity is punishing here, since they love to screw with humanity and since every violent act you fail to stop drains your support and therefore funding - this means air superiority is key. Get at least 3 bases up ASAP and make sure they cover at least a decent portion of the map. On that note, MiGs and enhanced torpedoes are some of the most important research projects in the earlygame, followed shortly by dropship tech. You can usually pick and choose where to send in the troops, but you need to be able to match your enemy in the air war ASAP. Noticing a pattern here?Also, ground combat is usually challenging to the point where you want to avoid night missions until the lategame, and start avoiding industrial areas around the midgame. Automatic weapons in close quarters and dangerous enemy types that run up in your face mean things will get very messy. Of course, if that's what you want, don't let me stop you from staging Stalingrad With Aliens."
76561198093755637,Recommended,223830,15136147,"Posted: 30 March, 2015",all,SSJ2 Gundalf,"What an amazing, remastered UFO: Enemy Unknown!At least that is what I want to write as a first line, but that won't be fair for this game. This game is more than just a remastered restart - it is more like ""take the ol' game, ged rid of everything anoying & add some cool stuff"" and well, it paid of!I wasn't playing this game for a long time, I didn't even finish my first full play ('cause of Long War mod in XCOM: Enemy Within) but still, I am going to recommend this to everyone, who cares about some good ol' strategic games. This game is more like a chess - you must think twice before you make a move; if you won't, your soldiers may not see the end of the day.Also beware, that this is an indie game. Graphic is not a concern here. For everything else - 9.5/10"
,Recommended,223830,12284819,"Posted: 28 September, 2014",all,Sgt. Pepper,"To put it simply, Xenonauts is an oldschool remake of the classic X-COM. And that means it retains the brutality of the original while still being incredibly fun to play.The graphics, while somewhat cartoony in places (notably cars) serve the art style well and convey the message of grimness throughout the game.Sound is fine, but some noises I found hurt my ears with headphones. Other than that not much of note aside from the good soundtrack.UI is somewhat complicated but easy to learn, while providing most of the vital information to keep your guys from not dying a horrible, awful, painful, and plasma-y death.Gameplay, the big G.It feels like X-COM. Not in a shoddy knock off way, but in a ""The devs knew what they were doing when they made this glorious game graced by the almighty Gaben himself"" way, complete with Time Units, Panics, and a boatload of potential ways for your poor plasma sh-err great soldiers to die. This includes fully playable air battles (which I recommend autoresolving for the most part), terror missions, abductions, and my love/hate favorite, the classic base defense.Have I mentioned how hard the game is? It is pretty difficult, but if you have played X-COM style games before, you will know what you're doing, but still get completely and utterly pimp slapped if you act like your soldiers are Rambos and Rambas.All in all, get it, or get plasma-ed."
