76561197971116718,Recommended,223830,18193813,"Posted: 25 September, 2015",all,Sirian,"This game is as close as I've seen to a ""clone"" of a previous game. That being said, the game it is cloning (X-com, the original) was a 5-star classic, and this version of it is actually quite good. Xenonauts managed to preserve nearly all the best parts of the original, while fixing some of its bigger flaws (especially in regard to the user interface) and avoiding introducing any new negative elements that step on the experience. I also played the X-com reboot, which enjoys the triple-A budget and graphics lacking in Xenonauts, and find Xenonauts to be the much better game. The X-com reboot forces you to choose (over and over) from a set of missions where you can only do one from the set (and the aliens win automatically in the places you opted not to go). I really, really -hate- that mechanic. Xenonauts gives you multiple threats at the same time, but gives you the option (over time, if you play well) to build multiple bases, acquire more interceptors, bomb the crashed alien ships you can't or don't wish to engage on the ground, even run multiple dropships full of troops, letting you eventually build up to where you can deal with more than one of those threats successfully -- perhaps even all of them, in some cases. That, I found, to be much more satisfying than the heavy-handed ""pick one and only one"" mission to do, where you are forced to sit and watch the world burn everywhere else. X-com2 is about to come out, and it looks like more of the same: smaller squads, only one base, only one dropship, a very heavy hand from the designer, channeling you down the road the way he wants you to travel at, at the pace he sets. Probably still has that cheap design shortcut of aliens not spawning on the map until you trigger their scripted appearance, when they always get a free move on you. (You can never catch them by surprise: there is no strategy that will let you get the drop on any of them at first encounter). Whereas in Xenonauts, the enemy units behave under the same rules you do: they are all on the map at the start of the combat and have to move using the same kind of Time Units restrictions that your troops must endure. You can lure some of the more aggressive alien types in to traps or crossfires, while others will patiently set traps for YOU that you have to figure out how to deal with. Luck plays a smaller role in Xenonauts, so of course that is the game that I favor.Do yourself a solid and pick up Xenonauts instead of the Xcom reboots. It's fun, challenging, and highly replayable, with more emphasis on strategy and tactics, more room for creativity and variation in how you tackle the challenges, and has more of the goodness that made the original X-com so special."
