76561198114959051,Recommended,223830,20284707,"Posted: 4 January, 2016",all,V-Bro - The Titan's Driver,"In XCOM: Enemy Unknown and Enemy Within, you fought battles.  In Xenonauts?  You fight a WAR!So far, that's the conclusion I've come having played and enjoyed both games.  After all, both have earned their praise for their own merits.  The XCOM successor reminded AAA that this type of strategy turn-based game is still desired.  And Xenonauts apparently captured the depth and spirit of the original XCOM from the 90s, though I wouldn't know since I didn't play it.  But I digress.I confess, this isn't a complete review yet, so I can only give a few main points right now.You heard the plot many times - humans must fight off the alien race.  But this ain't exactly a Spartan cutting everything down FPS style.The setting is 1979, and ""Xenonauts"" is the military organization put together by nations around the world (US, USSR, China, Europe, Latin America, all who can spare it).   Decades ago, an incident with an alien recon craft alerted Earth to 2 major realities -1.)  Aliens are coming.2.)  Any single nation is too hilariously outgunned to deal with them alone.Arrived they have.  Thousands of Aliens ships from Scouts to Warships orbit the Earth, but rather than just simply carpet bomb humanity, the Aliens intend to land down, infiltrate the nations, and conquer Earth using waves of soldiers and war machines.  For now, they can only send a few scouts to search for vulnerable targets and suitable sites to establish operations on the surface.This unique situation gives you time.  Time to intercept these scouts with specialized aircraft, then dispatch soldiers at landings or crash sites to extinguish the alien soldiers.  You will oversee these battles and guide them across a battle map until they have either extinguished all resistance or broken.  Once secure, all useful equipment, bodies, and weapons back to base for your scientists to analyze, and the rest is sold.  When your scientists develop the required technology, the engineers will build more powerful weapons, armor, vehicles, and aircraft.With better weapons and resources, your soldiers will more easily defeat aliens, and hopefully be more prepared when the Alien armies get bigger and change to more fearful tactics.That long paragraph I wrote is the game at its simplest, when it begins.  It won't stay simple.I'll have to summarize in a list.1. Build more bases around the world.  Supply them with their own aircraft, soldiers, and facilities, including Radar to detect incoming space ships.  You need funding to build and maintain ALL of it.2. Everything takes time to build, especially bases.  Plan accordingly.3. Otherwise, you can't handle the eventual wave of SEVERAL ships coming in, including transports, cruisers, bombers, and escorting fighter craft.  Yes, you need the ability to coordinate assaults at several locations.  Like I said, you're fighting a war.4. On top of that, several different kinds of species and ""droids"" will be sent upon your soldiers.  One tip especially:  FEAR THE REAPER!5. Keep advancing your tech, with lasers, then plasma, and get armor that will keep your soldiers from dying in ONE hit!6. Keep your bases defensible - They will be attacked.7. Do all you can to defend the nations funding you, but be prepared to make a hard choice of abandoning one if the aliens play a nasty hand.8. Prepare to capture and interrogate alien leaders, find out why they're here, and learn what it will take to beat this great enemy.So yes, a lot to deal with.  If you like XCOM:EU but felt it was too simplified, (they mostly just sent one UFO at a time in that game), here's the same game, only with emphasis on strategy - tenfold strategy."
