,Recommended,223830,10817376,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,failcopterwes,"I've only played about 15 hours of this so far, and I can safely say that this is, quite simply, one of the best turn based strategy games I've ever played. It's complicated, it's both epic in scope and self contained at the same time, and best of all, it expects you to just man up and deal with it when things go wrong.Essentially, its a straight remake of the 1990's original X-COM: UFO Defence (Or UFO: Enemy Unknown as it was known over here), but with the setting transposed and a few extra features added, such as the ability to airstrike crashes you don't want clear personally, which gets you money and saves time, but you don't get many resources or much soldier experience from it. Also added is a completely new interception system. Once your planes get in range you can direct them as they fly about in the air, until eventually they run out of fuel, ammunition, or everything crashes. It's all pretty awesome.The best part of it though is undoubtedly the vehicles. Unlike the recent XCOM: Enemy Unknown,  your transports can fit a small vehicle such as an armoured car into their loading bay instead of two soldiers. Once researched and built, these give your forces an undeniable edge as they suppress, expose or just otherwise blow the hell out of most of the enemies you encounter, with the tradeoff of limited ammunition and easily destroyed armour at close range.The only downsides I can really think of are a) the map shortage, although apparently there's a downloadable map pack that adds a load of new ones. It hasn't bothered me too much, but it's noticeable and b) you can't turn the camera, so occasionally the isometric veiwpoint obscures things a tad. But these are only minor things.Just get the damn thing already."
76561198048498273,Recommended,223830,10819179,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,SonofaGlitch,"Xenonauts . . .I'm not one who usually supports this new-fangled ""early access"" gaming craze. Usually. Xenonauts is one of my few exceptions.It's exactly what it claims to be - A complete remake of the original UFO: Enemy Unknown, but with a unique Cold War motif, different aliens, vastly improved graphics (compared to a game from 1994, that's to be expected) and an array of new features and tweaks that make the whole experience feel better and play far more smoothly. What itisn'tis a streamlined reboot, ala Firaxis' recent XCOM: Enemy Unknown/Within. For better and for worse, this is far more faithful to the original game (read: it's a lot harder to win, and learn how to play the game initially).That's what I wanted, and that's what I got. I couldn't be more pleased, and if this is what you're looking for, then I highly recommend that you stop reading and pick this game up IMMEDIATELY.That said, there are a few things keeping this from being 100% perfect.First, the game just needs a bit more . . . pizazz, for lack of a better word. It lacks an animated intro, a big missing feature compared to either the original UFO or the more recent XCOM. I know most wouldn't consider this a critical thing, but there was always something to booting up UFO and watching the Rob Liefield soldiers jump around firing mini-guns at fist shaking mutons that put you in the mood to do the same on the battlescape, and it's sorely missed when booting up Xenonauts. Obviously something fitting the darker style of 'Nauts would be needed rather than that silliness, but jumping straight into the title menu from the launcher just feels a bit jarring. Plus, one thing the new XCOM definitely nailed was giving the soldiers a lot of personality via little quips and callouts - considering this is a text focused game, it seems like a relatively simple thing that could have been/be added to make battles have just that extra little bit of character that would keep this up with Firaxis' bigger budget reboot.Additionally, this game couldreallyuse a tutorial mission or two for first-time players. While these players are obviously not the target demographic (that's fans of the original UFO like myself), the fact that there'snothingmakes the transition from UFO neophyte to veteran that much harder. It makes it a bit tougher to recommend to anyone unfamiliar with at least turn-based tactics games and UFO/XCOM in particular. For those in this group that are tempted by the game, I still think you should give this game a shot, just know that you're going to have to have more patience to learn how to play this game than most.After that though, this game is pretty much perfect as far as having an endlessly replayable Military versus Aliens Tactics and Strategy game. Enjoy, and keep watching those skies fellow Xenonauts!"
