76561198013089124,Recommended,223830,28855006,"Posted: 30 December, 2016",all,Handsome Matt,"It's a stronger sequel to XCOM:UFO Defense than anything that came out until XCOM Enemy Unknown. In some regards it's even better than Enemy Unknown. The ambient soundtrack is awesome, and makes for an uneasy feeling throughout the missions. I felt the same sweaty-palmed nervousness that the first game gave me every time I entered a terror mission. I think I let out a long groan and a quiet ""damnit, I hate those things"" when the chrysalis equivalent (the reaper) walked on the screen. Definitely had the nostalgia points going.It's obvious that this game was put together with love and care. The reports and xenopedia entries have a certain authenticity and wittiness to them that surpasses the original XCOM. I also thought the bitmap-esque style drawings had a certain charm to them. Overall quite polished and professional.But it also has fairly tight gameplay with a surprisingly good storyline. I've noticed that recent kickstarted/indie games tend to do one or the other well. Everything feels as fleshed out as a good 80s action flick (Rocky IV or Red Dawn, in keeping with the Cold War theme). Just enough good bits to keep you playing. Which is necessary because this game is unforgiving. Expect to restart missions often, unless you're fine with all your best troops dying. It's nice to have to earn the win, but it did border on frustrating. Especially when the difficulty would seemingly spike at random times.It's not without flaws though. Probably a 3rd of the way through the game all of my crack troops all forgot how to shoot their weapons. It's annoying to go from nailing targets repeatedly across the battlefield to missing the alien standing right next to you multiple times in a row. I also found the funding to be difficult to manage, I seemed to spend a few million dollars in less than 24 hours without explanation. Only to then spend the remainder of the month limping by on a budget of $1000. There didn't seem to be any connection to what projects or buildings I authorized and how much money was spent. I also found the base screens to be surprisingly flat, for a game with this much care put into it; it was irksome to see the same quotes each time I clicked into the screen. At least randomize the ways my lead researcher would show his disdain for me interrupting him!The one major flaw I found in the game though was the handling of alien technology. It was either sold off or destroyed. Which would be find except it was made clear that humans couldn't use the technology. This lead to the question ""Then who was buying it?"" It also meant that I was constantly playing catch up in the engineering game. Not enough money, not enough resources, not enough fun. I agree that in the late stages of XCOM it was ridiculous to have 500+ heavy plasma weapons in storage, but it is equally ridiculous to throw that entire concept away.All of these are minor inconveniences that do nothing to detract from the game. Even if it wasn't on sale, this is worth a buy."
